<br>
Bandwidth is certainly going to be an issue, we will open with a single DSL line and a single server.  I will be purchasing the server within the next few months and will by the most powerful machine I can afford at the time.  At the low end I would expect to have at least a 1.4g Mhz P4 with 512 ram.  Not sure what OS I will use, but I am planning on trying to get a copy of Window XP.<br>
<br>
Eventually we might want to add additional servers and bandwidth.   A dedicated T-1 starts at $245 per month, with is a bit out of my price range.  Depending on the number of players we have, it might be possible to fund that through a community effort. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/usiawnoverseas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Siawn Overseas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orc Pawn</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(10/4/01 8:23:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=127.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Techincal Stuff</span><hr size=1> Couple of questions...are they planning on having the server run on any OS?  Ie, Linux?<br>
<br>
For at least some of the zones you can farm out the bandwidth a little...especially low combat oriented type of zones (think temple in lavastorm).  I'd like to at least test and see how my cablemodem goes...have 3 computers here, might as well test it.  P2 400, 512 MB ram...perfect if its a linux box.  Speaking of which, probably a good idea for me to upgrade to red hat 7.1...5.2 just won't cut it.<br>
<br>
As far as emergency power, unless you plan on investing in a home generator, the UPS systems they have nowadays won't keep the computer powered up for long.  They are basically designed to alert you when the power goes down and give you time to save everything and shut down your system.  Most are rated for around 10 minutes worth of power, depending on the draw (don't expect to play quake 3 on your geforce3 video card, max res for very long... monitor+cpu will drain a good amount).<br>
<br>
What they will do is give you an audible alarm that'll be VERY obvious.  The ones we use on the ship are like 90 db...you can hear it several spaces away.  They also stabalize the electrical current going to your computer.  Contrary to popular belief, the current going to your house isn't perfect.  Its got spikes that can play hell with computers...even with surge protectors.  UPS's are very good security to make sure the surges don't harm computer components.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, you could be talking about a generator with sensors to detect when the electrical power going to the house fall to low and automatically kick in...diesel/gas powered I'm guessing.  If so, ignore all of this... If you can afford this, hehe wow bud.<br>
<br>
All that being said, a UPS would be a great thing to ensure data is not lost on the server...providing your close enough to shut it down/force the game to save.  If it goes down at 8am and both your and Kal are at work, not sure if its gonna help much. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/usiawnoverseas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Siawn Overseas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orc Pawn</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(10/4/01 8:25:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=127.topic&index=2>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Techincal Stuff</span><hr size=1> Did a little research, pasting it below.  Look down at the software section, some of these might be able to automatically save the system and shut it down.  Never worked with it myself so will have to defer to someone with more knowledge.<br>
