<br>
Thus an obvious problem.   Considering we will not have a professional tech staff available to make sure player's data is routinely saved, I will need to develop some sort of schedule.  This will have to be some sort of compromise between the obvious need to save data at certain intervals and the players ability to play.   Since I do have a full time job, the times when I could save the module (unless there is some sort of auto-save feature) would always be during prime play times.<br>
<br>
Should I close the module every day at 6:00 PM to save the characters or save the module once a week on an early saturday morning when few people would be effected.  Not sure on that call.  During the first couple of months it probably wouldnt matter much since there would be almost daily content adds to the module. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/uirtumble.showPublicProfile?language=EN>I R Tumble</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Guild Master</span><br>  Posts: 384<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(10/5/01 7:21:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=127.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Techincal Stuff</span><hr size=1> Network Administration and Enginering! Woot!<br>
<br>
The biggest power hog out of everything you have running is going to be your monitors. I have a spare monitor switch in storage you can use which will conserve not only desk space for you but it will also conserve power in the log run.<br>
<br>
The important thing you need to consider here is how long you want the equiptment to continue running after the power is lost. In most cases an hour is more than enough time to contact any users and have them backup whatever they are working on and have them exit their system.<br>
<br>
In this case if you have the monitor switch, the server, your computer, a hub and a monitor connected to even the smallest APC unit you should stay operational for about 30 min. However, you could purchase a larger unit in the $500 range to provide about 2 hours of use for the above mentioned items.<br>
<br>
Beyond that range you start talking about the expandable units like I use here. While the individual battery packs are only about $200 the controller unit is about $2,000. But, you simply add a battery unit in a daisy chain any time you add more servers or other components.<br>
<br>
Somewhere here I have a program from APC which is supposed to help determine your power needs and which of their units would best adapt to that situation. I'll try to hunt it down for you sometime today.<br>
<br>
Oh! I also have copies of Windows NT and 2000 if you want to actually turn the computer into a server as opposed to it being another workstation on your network.<br>
